We assume that symptomatic individuals make, on average, between two and three effective contacts. This value is set accordingly to the current estimate of the basic reproduction number [11, 12, 15, 16]. The infectiousness measure is set to represent the viral load observations reported in [13, 21, 22], the peak of which is reached within a few days after symptom onset. Based on the currently available information, we assume the same viral load shape between mild, severe, and asymptomatic individuals. The total length is informed using the observations of symptomatic cases reported in Zou et al. [13], and it is computed as the convolution of incubation and symptomatic period. Asymptomatic individuals are assumed to have lower transmission compared to symptomatic ones. We set the asymptomatic reproduction number, \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
